    <string name="about_me_content">Hello! I am the creator and lead developer behind Aircraft, a retro-styled 2D vertical-scrolling shooter built for Android with Kotlin.\n\nMy background spans Android application development, DevOps, and quality assurance. Over the years I have worked on both enterprise software and personal creative projects, using technologies such as Kotlin, Java, Jetpack Compose, Room, Firebase, and GitHub Actions. That mix of experience helps me build code that is both robust and practical.\n\nAircraft started as a personal challenge: build a full-featured arcade shooter with only the Android SDK and a SurfaceView canvas. No game engine, no Unity, and no third-party gameplay framework. The game uses direct canvas rendering, custom collision detection, and carefully managed threading to deliver smooth gameplay at 30 FPS.\n\nI care deeply about fundamentals. Modern frameworks are powerful, but there is real value in understanding rendering loops, bitmap scaling, multi-threaded state, and collision logic at a low level. This project is where I explore those details and turn them into a playable experience.\n\nOutside of coding, I enjoy open-source work, technical writing, and mentoring. I like sharing what I learn and helping other developers grow. Aircraft reflects both my interest in classic arcade games and my interest in building software the hard way when that teaches something useful.\n\nI plan to keep expanding the project with more enemies, more power-ups, and more polished gameplay, while continuing to modernize parts of the app UI with Jetpack Compose. If you have feedback or ideas, feel free to reach out through GitHub.</string>
    <string name="about_me_project_content">Aircraft is a 2D vertical-scrolling shooter for Android written entirely in Kotlin. The player controls a jet, fires upward, clears enemy waves, collects power-ups, and survives through ten time-based levels that end with boss battles.\n\nThe game engine is built on a custom SurfaceView with a dedicated rendering thread that targets 30 FPS. Core objects such as the player aircraft, enemies, bullets, explosions, and power-ups are drawn directly on a Canvas, with collision checks and update logic handled in the game loop.\n\nThe project includes multiple power-up types, persistent score tracking with Room, a bound MusicService for audio, three difficulty levels, and localization in English and Chinese. It also uses GitHub Actions for CI together with Firebase Crashlytics and Firebase Analytics.\n\n%1$s</string>
    <string name="about_me_project_repo_url" translatable="false">https://github.com/tobecrazy/Aircraft</string>
    <string name="about_me_project_repo_line">%1$s: %2$s</string>

